findings: The URI: "http://192.168.1.142:82/" has a parameter named: "page" with value: "add-to-your-blog.php", which is very uncommon and requires manual inspection.
The server header for the remote web server is: "Apache/2.4.7 (Ubuntu)".
The URI: "http://192.168.1.142:82/" has a parameter named: "do" with value: "toggle-bubble-hints", which is very uncommon and requires manual inspection.
The URI: "http://192.168.1.142:82/" has a parameter named: "page" with value: "./documentation/vulnerabilities.php", which is very uncommon and requires manual inspection.
The x-powered-by header for the target HTTP server is "PHP/5.5.9-1ubuntu4.25".

The URI: "http://192.168.1.142:82/" has a parameter named: "PathToDocument" with value: "documentation/how-to-access-Mutillidae-over-Virtual-Box-network.php", which is very uncommon and requires manual inspection.
The remote Web server has a custom configuration, in which any not implemented methods that are invoked are defaulted to GET instead of returning a "Not Implemented" response.
The URI: "http://192.168.1.142:82/" has a parameter named: "page-to-frame" with value: "styling.php?page-title=Styling with Mutillidae", which is very uncommon and requires manual inspection.
The content of "http://192.168.1.142:82/" references a non existent domain: "192.168.1.142". This can be a broken link, or an internal domain name.
Fingerprinted this host as a *nix system. Detection for this operating system is weak, "if not windows then linux".
The URL: "http://192.168.1.142:82/documentation/mutillidae-installation-on-xampp-win7.pdf" returned an empty body, this could indicate an application error.

The authentication plugin failed 3 consecutive times to get a valid application session using the user-provided configuration settings.

The `autocomplete` authentication plugin will be disabled.

The following are the last log messages from the authentication plugin:

 - Logging into the application with user: admin
 - Failed to find an HTML login form at http://host.tld/login (id: 327). The authentication plugin is most likely incorrectly configured.
 - Failed to find an HTML login form at http://host.tld/login (id: 327). The authentication plugin is most likely incorrectly configured.
The most accurate fingerprint for this HTTP server is: "['Microsoft-IIS/7.0', 'Microsoft-HTTPAPI/2.0']".
The URL: "http://192.168.1.142:82/webservices/soap/ws-hello-world.php" is a Web Services Description Language page. This requires manual analysis to determine the security of the web service.
The URL: "http://192.168.1.142:82/webservices/" has a directory indexing vulnerability.

SQL injection in a MySQL database was found at: "http://192.168.1.142:82/hints-page-wrapper.php", using HTTP method GET. The sent data was: "level1HintIncludeFile=1%272%223" The modified parameter was "level1HintIncludeFile".

A potential (most probably a false positive than a bug) buffer-overflow was found when requesting: "http://192.168.1.142:82/hints-page-wrapper.php", using HTTP method GET. The data sent was: "level1HintIncludeFile=AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA".

The `autocomplete` authentication plugin was never able to authenticate and get a valid application session using the user-provided configuration settings

The application has no protection against Click-Jacking attacks. All the received HTTP responses were found to be vulnerable, only the first 25 samples were captured as proof.

items.Name: Insecure X-XSS-Protection header usage
items.Description:
The remote web server sent 5 HTTP responses with the X-XSS-Protection header with a value of "0", which disables Internet Explorer's XSS filter. The first ten URLs which sent the insecure header are:
 - http://192.168.1.142:82/
 - http://192.168.1.142:82/?QCMBem5=id&uname -a=
 - http://192.168.1.142:82/?QCMBem5=<script>alert(1)</script>
 - http://192.168.1.142:82/?QCMBem5=exec master..xp_cmdshell dir
 - http://192.168.1.142:82/?QCMBem5=ocVCAvB

items.Name: Interesting HTML comment
items.Description:
A total of 5 HTTP requests contained an HTML comment that includes HTML tags: " I think the database password is set to blank or perhaps samurai.
			It depends on whether you installed this web app from irongeeks site or
			are using it inside Kevin Johnsons Samurai web testing framework.
			It is ok to put the password in HTML comments because no user will ever see
			this comment. I remember that security instructor saying we should use the
			framework comment symbols (ASP.NET, JAVA, PHP, Etc.)
			rather than HTML comments, but we all know those
			security instructors are just making all this up. ". The first ten matching URLs are:
 - http://192.168.1.142:82/
 - http://192.168.1.142:82/?QCMBem5=id&uname -a=
 - http://192.168.1.142:82/?QCMBem5=<script>alert(1)</script>
 - http://192.168.1.142:82/?QCMBem5=exec master..xp_cmdshell dir
 - http://192.168.1.142:82/?QCMBem5=ocVCAvB
